<div><a name="page-1"></a></div>
<p>During the height of the Cold War, the United States and Soviet Union engaged in a struggle across many frontsâ€”economically, politically, diplomatically, and more. As part of this they were competing for hearts and minds of nations caught between the two superpowers.</p>
<p>The Space Race in the 1960s was all about geopolitics. By accomplishing feats in space, Americans and Soviets were showing off the supremacy of their culture and scientific communities. Ultimately, landing NASA astronauts on the Moon offered the terrestrial world a huge statement on why the American way was better.</p>
<p>When the geopolitical imperative for this ran out, so did the money.</p></div><p><a href="https://arstechnica.com/?p=1977401#p3">Read 14 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href="https://arstechnica.com/?p=1977401&comments=1">Comments</a></p>